,Not Recommended,246090,12286031,"Posted: 28 September, 2014",all,Brocephalopod,"Early access brings the unfortunate risk of being burned and this game is the first one to have burned me badly enough to write a negative review.First of all, this is practically a demo that absolutely does not capture what makes this genre ""fun"". Generally the interesting thing about base building games is not about how you can create a utopia where nothing goes wrong, but how your base will eventually come to its inevitable end.Spacebase DF-9 fails to spark any continued enjoyment because of how quickly one can create a stable base without having to worry about anything bad ever happening. One playthrough was all it took to figure out all the kinks for the next time, where it is entirely possible to reach a state where everything simply balances itself out. This can be attributed to the fact that the game has a veryshortlist of features.Theshortlist of rooms have an incrediblyshortlist of items one can add to it, so constructing a base on the second playthrough provides almost the exact same experience. It is not surprising how shallow this game feels compared to other games from the genre, even before you are hit by the realization that the learning curve is really just a horizontal line.The random events and the citizens ""dynamic"" behavior do not add a lot of variety, which is something that also quickly realized as you build your base. Understanding the patterns of theshortlist of events the game throws at you does not take a lot of figuring out, which is not surprising given the fact that you can count these on one hand. To make things even worse, any negative event that can happen is easily preventable with the aforementionedshortlist of items at your disposal.The only challenging element this game presents, is the incredibly stupid AI that is set on destroying itself as early as building the very first airlock for the base. God help them if they are apart of your mining crew and there happens to be two airlocks to your base, because they are more likely to asphyxiate in space than they are picking which one is closer so they do not die.Again, all these negative aspects can be attributed due to the fact that this title is featureINCOMPLETEand will probably remain so, unless it builds a decent modding community (which is incredibly unlikely to happen given the current state). The keyword here isshort, as in the feature list, the amount of time this game was given development time until its ""full"" release, and any enjoyment you can get out of it.I would be lying if I said I had never been so disappointed by a game before, but certainly not with a game that I was so excited to see completed. In the end I, and several other hopefuls lost out on $20-25 on a game that will never be finished. And while they did not lie to us about ""silently pulling the plug"", but they certainly lied about delivering us a ""complete"" game. With them violating my trust, I will never be purchasing another early access title or Double Fine game ever again."
