,Not Recommended,246090,12308307,"Posted: 30 September, 2014",all,Insignus,"As an early access game, DF9 was decent. There was definable progress. I'll admit it, it was fun. There were bugs, and early access gripes, but the EA rule I use is that ""As long I can visualize this being finished, done, and fun, I can consider spending money on it."" DF9 met those criteria. However, as the game has moved abruptly to a ""release"", and with the complete stoppage of new features, Double Fine has fallen far, far short of even approaching their planned development milestones. Further, the lack of believable rationales, detailed explanations, or even breakdowns about why this came about mean that I can't in good faith recommend that you purchase this game, or any future titles from Double Fine productions until some form of publically disclosed management shakeup takes place.They reportedly raised approximately half a million dollars to develop this game. They then stopped development, citing financial reasons. They do not appear to have then offered any breakdown of where said money went. They are now confused, as people are angry and asking ""WHERE DID THAT MONEY GO!?"" The statements I have reviewed do not appear to show that this logical connectoin has been made.The final nail in the coffin was a ""AWESOME DEV PROCESS GREAT JOB"" timeline that was issued as a ""We're sorry we took your money, but don't pay attention to the archived feature lists we pumped for months about what we were going to do, instead read this sleek graphic that shows what we DID do! JUST DONT COMPARE THE TWO!"" Their conduct in this and other products leads me to the following unfortunate conclusion regarding Double Fine Productions:They simply are not a worthwhile investment for your consumer dollars. This is not the first time this endgame has come about for one of their product. That is not to say Double Fine is an intrinsically bad company, or that they cannot make good games. But I simply cannot justify spending money on early access titles from them now or in the future.At this point, Double Fine serves as an argument for Valve to more or less micro-audit game development companies, even basic indie ones, for management practices. Whether that is feasible or a correct response is a different matter, but Double Fine's performance definitely elicits that reaction. That or open up a ""Developer Review"" page to trash talk developers (This would also be a bad idea, but it is my inclination in response).A more reasonable option would be for Valve to construct a form of ""Warning Stick"" that it can publically shake at developers who mis-behave in such a fashion. A ""We're reviewing their sales agreement"" or ""We're considering yanking their priviledge to post on early access"" type of statement, to remind developers that Early Access is not a kickstarter equivalent, but is rather an opportunity to generate interest and feedback on your products."
