76561198072854315,Not Recommended,246090,12162069,"Posted: 20 September, 2014",all,delayman2,"I was initially excited for the game. A sim colony game in space. What's not to like? I used to play Startopia (awesome!) and Space Colony (pretty good!) so I was pumped for another game of the kind.I like that the game does not take itself too seriously. You got funny dialogues, weird aliens, and spacebook. It makes for a comfortable feel too it. The colors are vibrant and the interaction between crew members are kinda funny.The ability to create your own base and style it the way you want is also very interesting. It makes for a unique base layout each time you make a new game.And then there are the things that bother me. First, for a base that supposed to feel like home, there's very little items you can put in a room. A potted plant, a monitor, a dresser, a rug, some shelves, and a couple of neon signs are your ONLY decorations. There isn't even any way you can recolor it so you're stuck with the same items in every room.Second, You can only rotate the camera from north to east facing. That will apply to every item too. It's really frustrating as it limits your design option.Third, There are still a lot of bugs or unfinished issues (that they might address in the future) No matter what you do at the moment, your base will fail either due to depressed crew members that results into raging and destruction of rooms and equipment or raiders killing everybody even if your security personel had all the upgrades available. Some suggested that you put a decorative object almost every other tile to stave off depression but we shouldn't have to do that. You also had that design issue wherein the item looks like it's floating rather than attached to the wall. Crew members can actually go behind it (i.e. Food replicator, monitor)Ultimately, I felt like I was ripped off. To put more context, Doublefine did say that they 'might' add more based on the development map that they laid out but with the current and future content (1.0) that will come out, it is wholly unreasonable for the 30$ they are asking. It felt like they just gave up midway through.The worst thing about this is that since they are giving the community access to the source code, they now wash their hands off it. It is now the responsibility of the community to make the game great. Oh sure, they said they'll be sticking around...for bug fixes.I knew there were dangers of buying early-access games but I couldn't stop myself. Now I regret it. Don't make the same mistake"
76561198018188786,Not Recommended,246090,12228492,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,Descriptor,"This could have been a fun an interesting game if there was anything to do with your base after the first hour or so. Instead, you will just run out of material to mine and slowly watch your base die.Or quickly, depending on the raiders.Unfortunatly, the developers rather surprisingly have seemed to have just given up completely on the game, rushing it to version 1.0 even though there isn't even a reasonable end game experiance. If they actually added everything they were planning, it might have been interesting. However, as is, it's simply not worth the surprisingly high cost. While the gameplay that is there is fairly strong and enjoyable to play, there's simply not enough for $25, and it looks like there never will be.Long story short, avoid this game at its current price. If you see it on a massive (like, selling for less than $5) sale, maybe try it, but honestly, there's really not much here, and certainly very little replayability. If you want a base building game but aren't neckbearded enough for Dwarf Fortress, try out Gnomoria instead. It controls like a potatoe and is pretty hard to get into, but there's also a lot more gameplay to be had, and for a third the price."
