,Not Recommended,246090,12178075,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,Chumprock,"I purchased this game during a steam sale on september 3 for 50% off early access.I had been following the progress for a while, and was hoping for a more finished product, but when I watched the Alpha 6 video from Double Fine, it looked like this update finally added some more content and there were also certain assurances from JP, the lead developer, that they would strive for better communication in regards to content and issues in the future. I decided to pay up and try it out.Well, it was still very broken. Aside from the known bugs that weren't resolved, the new ""mood system"" introduced some hugely game breaking bugs and it was hard to progress very far at all in the game without having to restart for one reason or another.I frustratingly put the game down for the weekend, and only played it a few more times until they ironed out some of the more severe mood bugs by 6e-f.Once those game breakers were (pretty much) out of the way, I was able to successfully establish a base and build it to fair size before wondering the inevitable.. ""okay, now what?"" of an unfinished sandbox game. The derelict ships provide a little interest, but can sometimes be a pain to deal with. The breaches could be a very fun aspect of the game, but instead balance issues make them either ridiculously easy, or painfully hard with no real explanation as to why one way or another.This lead me to decide (as I have done with other Early Access titles) to ""put the game down"" for a bit, and come back later when they have added some more content to make the game more interesting and challenging to play.It is now two weeks later, and the lead developer has stated that they will be finalizing this game and releasing 1.0 in a month.This is a woefully unfinished game that is severely lacking in content. While the idea and core features seem real enticing, the truth is there really isn't much at all to do and I dont see the developer adding that much more before actual release.If you would like a ""space base"" type game, I would suggest an alternative in Startopia. Yes, it's almost 15 years old, but its funny and entertaining and actually has goals and stuff to do. I guarantee you will get much better gaming enjoyment out of Startopia than this unfinished, yet released product."
