76561198011508807,Not Recommended,246090,8779371,"Posted: 19 January, 2014",all,desertgiant3197,"Spacebase DF-9, or as I like to call it “The one game where I want to throw everyone out the airlock and watch them all die” is in my opinion one of the reasons early access games should not be on steam. While the page fully warns people that this is still in its alpha stages it should not have been allowed to until at least a better running beta. As of right now the game is computer destroyingly broken as there are multiple problems with the game.The Intro: As of right now there is not even a full bare bones intro to this game. While when first picking the area you will settle in you see multiple aspects in the upper right corner which mean nothing to you. However it does give the player some heads up after picking it what everything means. That is the only good thing I can say about the intro as is. The next second you are placed in space with three aliens and a pod which can be broken down for scrap and a few minutes of oxygen for each to try and figure out how to build a base. While I understand people hate the idea of tutorials that really drag on I would have preferred at least something to give me more information. My first time playing my entire crew died because instead of building as I instructed they mostly floated around space and then began to panic when their oxygen got low because no one worked.The AI: Ok… Day One: Garry’s Incident I feel is one of the best examples of bad AI… this nearly reaches the same level of incompetence. In order for a crew member to do anything you must assign a job and where they will be in regards to some of the jobs like mining and building. While that’s fine by itself the AI doesn’t know what to do often times. They will lounge about the base or flat out ignore build orders or security beacons for when intruders come in guns blazing or fires because… I have absolutely no idea. The AI is unresponsive and more lazy than helpful and I feel like this would have been aided greatly by being able to tell them what to do The Sims style but the AI of course has free will… the free will to walk around doing nothing while I have set up a build order for oxygen recyclers which they need to live while their oxygen quickly is used up.Building: There is barely any direction as to what to build when starting but common sense plays a part here. Of course they need oxygen, food, and a way for more resources and while all those work when the AI actually does their job… the rest is very lacking. There is no explanation as to why a pub, or a reactor, or really anything is important beyond just common sense guiding my actions to make me build them because, they are there so they must be useful. After all if they can make their own food they stop eating the same stuff from the food replicators. But again things don’t seem to need reactors for power or crew quarters, or fitness rooms, or a pub since things work without them. Again direction would be nice here and even diversity since for example there is only one air recycler, no better one.There is more I could go on about and while I love Double Fine… I cannot in good conscience recommend this game to anyone until at EARLIEST its full release. But even then I would wait a few months if this is any indication of what the full game will be like."
,Not Recommended,246090,11996542,"Posted: 6 September, 2014",all,LtKillPuppy,"☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☠☠☠  Avoid, avoid, avoid, avoid!  ☠☠☠☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰☰This game has been classified as hazardous space debris.  Set your navicomps to avoid this sector at all costs, lest you find yourself wasting space credits.UPDATE: Developer has released the game as ""done.""  Oh, but we'll get the source code so we can finish it ourselves, right?  Right??  Well, let me say this:  Tim Schafer is the new Peter Molyneux.  *drops mic and walks away from Double Fine forever*UPDATE 2:  Just played 1.05, the ""release"" version of the game.  Some of the bugs I've mentioned have been addressed, but only a few.  Now features a ""tutorial"" level that is basically just a pre-built base with some lame text overlays telling you to perform a few tasks.  I played the level after the tutorials were complete, and was immediately swamped by a continous stream of raider vessels.  Base went from 12 occupants to just 1, and when I saw that last ""Raider breach vessel incoming!"" message I just quit the game and un-installed it again.Pros:☑  Er.  I wish it were a good game that had potential?  Cuz I would love me a Sim Starbase game.Cons:☒  Very buggy user interface.  I commonly had to ""trick"" the game to build an item by building another and then canceling it before completing it in order to get it to build the second item (which is the item I wanted in the first place).  If items overlap, then it is impossible to click on one or more of the overlapped items.  (Say if you have a claim-territory flag that is overlapped by an oxygen generator.)☒  Obtuse needs and wants system.  My crew fights and kills each other, and I am never sure why without carefully inspecting each cluttered needs/wants screen for each crew member.☒  I've lost dozens of crew without even really knowing why.  The notification bar fills up with tons of ""XXXX needs medical attention"" and ""XXXX is dead"" messages before I can even react to whatever is putting my crew in danger.☒  Your first base is going to result in dead astronauts.  So will your second, third, fourth and likely fifth.  Margins are extremely thin at the beginning of the game, so if you screw up in the least (such as build a room too small to hold a refinery, without knowing how big that refinery is) you have to start over.  There is no way to undo or fix a build mistake, so if you make any at the critical first few minutes of the game, then kiss your space-butt goodbye.☒  Zoning system is clunky and requires you to build a special-purpose room to simply place one item.☒  Annoying fixed view that cannot be rotated, nor is there a ""fade behind"" effect when someone or something is behind another object, so it's easy to lose people or things.  This will likely never change either, because while the crew are rendered as 3D models, it's clear the walls and objects are static sprites, and if the devs didn't account for rotating views at this point in the dev cycle, they probably never will.☒  Overall quite buggy.  UI elements end up becoming corrupt, crew get stuck in rampaging loops and can never be subdued, miners will drop ore in the middle of space during a crisis and never pick it back up, etc.☒  Feels very unpolished, and like an early WIP.  Expected more progress for this game since the last time I looked at it (about a year ago)."
