,Recommended,246090,12217745,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,DJPoopPants,"Really cool, really ambitious game that stands strong despite missing it's initial target. It reminds me a lot of old bullfrog games like theme hospital, but with a tremendous amount of depth. Doublefine did a really great job of providing this depth without loading it down in complexity. The result is a really fascinating environment where the player spends as much (maybe more) time observing than controlling. The world is continually evolving and full of surprises, but never feels out of your control.If you're looking for something a little diffrent and enjoy systems driven design/narrative, definitely check it out."
,Recommended,246090,9720260,"Posted: 3 April, 2014",all,Polydactyl1,"Do you like resource management type games? Do you like simulation type games? Do you like science fiction? If you answered yes to two of the previous questions you should check out Spacebase DF-9. Even though this is an Early Access Game there is still enough playability and fun in it to occupy hours of your life.Basically you build a space station or as the name suggests a Spacebase. You do this by laying out rooms and zoning them for specific tasks. At first you'll need an airlock and a life support system so that your virtual Spacebase residents can breath. As you play, you'll discover that you need to expand, and that takes resources. You'll need to build more rooms and different types of zones to make your Spacebase function. Things like refineries, sleeping quarters and pubs. Yes, they have pubs in space.To add to the gameplay each of your Spacebase residents has his or her special skill set. You need to assign them tasks based on their individual skills or train them in new ones, if you wish. As they get better at their tasks the station starts to hum along nicely. As you progress, you'll discover that the natives get restless and you'll need to attend to their complaints and unhappiness by building new rooms or maybe mixing up their work routine.All that is enough to keep you busy, but there is more. Every now and again a spaceship will pass by. They can be friendly folk and join your Spacebase or they can be your worst day in space. Sometimes you can weasel your way out of sticky situations but eventually something is going to rain on your Spacebase. You'll need to prepare for that eventuality and defend your Spacebase if you want to hold onto it.This is an Early Access Game and it’s in Alpha 4b as of this writing. Even so, there is plenty of fun to be had with this game. Double Fine Productions, the developer, is actively releasing updates. They are shooting for updates on a monthly basis and that’s good.Now I don’t want to mislead you. I’m having a ton of fun with this game, but it is and Early Access Game and it’s still in Alpha. That means it’s not for everyone. The game isn’t finished. It’s not even close to finished. It’s Alpha. Don’t buy this game expecting a polished game. Even if you have Beta tested before, keep in mind that this is pre-beta.That said, this game promises to be something extremely fun to play. If you want to be in on the ground floor and watch, as well as give feedback, as the game develops then you should definitely pick up a copy of Spacebase DF-9. It’s okay, the waters warm, jump in. You will have fun."
