,Not Recommended,246090,11501360,"Posted: 31 July, 2014",all,Multiplex10,"I really love the idea, but I'm not totally in love with the execution — yet. I still recommend playing it, but I feel like at this point, any new games I start will play out pretty much identically to what I'm doing.It seems like there's a good structure for a game, but it doesn't take much time at all to get a pretty decent, stable population (until raiders or parasites come along and decimate you). Medicine could be fleshed out more. Science and technology need to be fleshed out more. Facilities should be upgradeable in some capacity — better entertainment facilities, better food replicators, whatever. A bit more of a personality to the citizens would be interesting. Maybe they form groups to make demands of you?Even in the premise (story?) of the game, who IS the player?I look forward to seeing what is tweaked and added to this game, though! The graphics are a lot of fun. There's a ton of potential here.UPDATE: After Spacebase was unceremoniously shoved out of early access, I have to change my review from a thumbs up to a thumbs down. It was a promising game, but decidedly incomplete. Knowing that the developers have basically given up on it changes things: my thumbs-up review before was based on its potential. This thumbs down review is based on what it actually IS -- a half-finished game with a lot of interesting ideas and nothing much for the player to do with them."
,Not Recommended,246090,8433883,"Posted: 30 December, 2013",all,BOT Rob,"I really loved this game, but the sheer ballsiness of the developers on this project has caused me to have to flip my thumb downward. Instead of continuing development on this game, a potential gem for simulation games, they're finishing their current tasklist then moving it on to the community to complete the game. I could see this for $5, as a personal project from someone who doesn't necessarily need the money, but not from a renowned developer like Double Fine.To avoid railing on the devs, who actually did a fine job(bah dum tiss), there are quite a few things wrong with the game itself.Pros1. The few stylized art pieces of the game, especially the character portraits are really charming.2. Base development is very interesting and lends a lot to imagination, since the base can be torn down and rebuilt as well. You don't even have to keep oxygen in the rooms. :)3. The music is pretty catchy.4. The UI isreallyclean.Cons1. Citizens sleep for an unreasonably long time. A bit over 4 minutes wouldn't be much time IRL, but considering that the game isn't running on real time, it's basically like taking a member of the community into a temporary community. If there's a tiredness stat, there's only one static way to rejuvenate it, and it takes forever. Might as well just skip making beds in the first place.2. Raiders and other attacks are completely devastating to a young space station. Not necessarily a con, but having to stop working on a base expansion in order to tear down a docked station is a bit discouraging.2a. You can't tweak any of these settings - meaning that raiders, pirates, parasites, (I don't believe Killbots are there yet), and meteor storms just happen.3. Personal inventory is hastily implemented. Essentially it's just a clutter simulator now.4. Space beds take up too much room, making personal bedrooms an undesirable solution. Yes: you wouldn't want to join a space station that doesn't give you a comfortable place to live, but I doubt that's a necessity when you're just trying to keep your people oxygenated.5. No ability to customize characters or furniture.6. Spacefrog logs tend to take up a lot of the dev log, but essentially it's just text-based in a personally unused section of the character profile panel.7. Once your base is maxed out, there are few activities aside from keeping your food chain going, keeping oxygen/energy machines going, and patrolling the base. No hostile interaction, no other space bases to communicate with, no overworld map for shipping minerals back-and-forth, no super-future tech. Just more of the same, with decreasing intrinsic threat.8. If you don't play by the dev's rules when entering derelicts, they're completely bugged. For example: if you want to enter a derelict by punching a hole in the wall and sucking the raiders out into the vacuum, then the derelict will remain hidden by the fog-of-war. You'd have to rebuild the wall then explore it with a security team (good luck if anyone's sleeping). After that, if you unclaim the rooms then they'll go back into FoW, iirc. There's an oxygen generator on the derelict? Oops, looks like your base's oxygen support counter just incremented and you'll need to unclaim it and quickly destroy it, good luck if anyone's sleeping. Or you'll need to unclaim it and wait for it to destroy itself, or get to it before it can go back under the FoW.Basically, imagine if the Prison Architect guys quit this time a year or two ago. The game would still be fun and playable, but there would be just such a lack of depth.This game isn't done. There is an entire host of ideas and game mechanics than can be iimplemented to make this game a true genre piece. Instead, the devs are just going to quit on it to go lurk behind some other title hardcore simulation fans probably won't buy.Bah.-----Old ReviewSpacebase DF-9 is probably one of the best build-it-yourself management games I've played in a long time. You're able to build any kind of station you desire in any pattern, lending as much or as little to design and preparation as you'd like. The game is an early access, but the devs have laid out a lot of functionality that's going to be added. For fans of this genre and as an early alpha, this game is definitely worth picking up."
