,Not Recommended,246090,13349375,"Posted: 13 December, 2014",all,Unknown Zombie,"Playing this game will only frustrate you. This is a management game that is set up in a way that should minimize micro-management of your denizens and let you concentrate on the bigger picture. The citizens of your base are expected to be able to make decisions on their own using their AI. Unfortunately, their AI is nowhere near complete enough to make this feasible. Quite often your entire base will spiral out of control because of events that are set in motion by something a citizen did or did not do because of poor AI.Because the game was apprently intended to lean away from micro-managing each citizen, you are powerless to make a citizen do something they are neglecting to do and you cannot stop them from doing something you don't want them doing. There just are no means to give individual commands, which causes too many problems to make this a fun game. Far too often your base will die off for reasons completely out of your control because one person was hell-bent on doing something wrong.One example: I've had a base sent into a depression spiral because my doctor kept deciding that she would rather lift weights for hours instead of pick up dead bodies that were accumulating from repeated raider attacks. The numerous bodies around the base put everyone into foul moods causing them to constantly fight one another, eventually thinning their own ranks so much that I could no longer defend against raider attacks. All of this could have been avoided had I been able to force my doctor to pick up bodies. Instead, all I could do was watch her and hope that she stops lifting weights long enough to pick up a body or two on her own.Another example: I've had a base where a small fire killed every single crew member because each and every one of them insisted on attempting to stomp the fire out with their feet instead of using the fire extinguisher posted right beside the door to the room."
