,Not Recommended,246090,14600839,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,DAOWAce,"One of the more promising management games I've seen.To me, it was like Space Colony mixed with a bit of Startopia, both games I absolutely loved.I was very much looking forward to playing the finished game.They never finished it.Midway through alpha development they 'ran out of money'.  This resulted in them slapping a poor excuse for a tutorial onto the game and fixing only a handful of the hundreds of bugs the game had and releasing it.  They stuck around for 6 more patches fixing even more bugs, and the game still has dozens of bugs.They released the source code expecting modders to finish developing the game and continued to sell it for full price.It's still being sold, incomplete and extremely buggy.This is the game that dragged Double Fine's reputation into the dirt, and rightfully so.If you choose to give them money (or get it elsewhere, as it's essentially abandonware at this point), you will have a few hours of fun, especially if you loved management games of old; but play it longer than that and all you'll experience is complete frustration at the bugs and the general incompleteness of the game.  Every now and again I decide I want to play it again.. and can barely even get a colony started, let alone last more than an hour without crippling bugs breaking the entire thing.You can pickup Space Colony HD for $2.50 (on sale) on GoG or Steam.  It's a much, much better game.  If you want something a bit different, Startopia is great too, but you'll need to get a widescreen FoV fix to play it properly on modern displays.---Update: There's a fan patch for the game that starts to introduce new features and attempts to fix some of the issues with the game.  Unfortunately, it has issues itself and neither experience is a very good one.  Development on it is also very slow as it's by amateur part time modders who seem to have issues every release (including just flat out missing files).Maybe in the future it'll be well developed enough to actually fix and improve and add to the game, but as of right now, the game is still alpha quality no matter what.But hey, at least the game only costs $1 now (on sale), right?"
